description:
A male Tailed Copper (Lycaena arota), discovered along the banks of Stevens Creek as it was nectaring on some Shortpod Mustard (Hirschfeldia incana).  It cooperated enough to give me a couple of decent shots of its upperwings, but not cooperative enough for even a single shot of its underwings.  Fortunately, this is a species that can be identified from just the characteristics of its upperwings alone.  The key field marks here:  (1) The elongated, trapezoidal shape of this butterfly's forewings and the roundly triangular shape of its hind wings;  (2) the small tail along the termen of each hind wing; (3) the coppery orange to coppery brown color of this butterfly's upperwings (usually the wings are darker than this, but here, the wings are exhibiting a fair amount of fading and wear); (4) the small, dark brown dots along the ternus of the hind wings; and (5) the heavy orange line around the largest two or three of these dots.

Photographed at Stevens Creek County Park in Cupertino, CA.

References:
1) Shapiro, Arthur M., and Manolis, Timothy D. (2007).  Field Guide to the Butterflies of the San Francisco Bay and Sacramento Valley Regions.  Berkeley: University of California Press.  See p. 123 and Plate 9 for the species description.
2) "Tailed Copper - Lycaena arota,"  Butterflies and Moths of North America.  Retrieved from https://www.butterfliesandmoths.org/species/Lycaena-arota on 10/29/19.
3) "Lycaena arota," Wikipedia. Retrieved from https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lycaena_arota on 10/29/19.

description: While hiking Boy Scout Tree Trailer we encountered the weirdest thing. During the first walk by we found a near-death mouse and a half eaten mouse near each other and a large redwood. The mouse that was still barely alive was still moving but not a lot. It was acting very lethargic. We left it alone and assumed a predator, such as a weasel had gotten to the mice. About 40 min later we walked by the mice again and we found a presumed adult mouse cannibalizing the already dead and half-eaten mouse. We sat there and watched the mouse eat the dead mouse for about 5 minutes before we left it alone and continued down the trail.

description: This Cicada kept flying from branch to branch, clicking excitedly while I was trying to follow it to take it's photo. At one point it flew at me, circled me and landed on my iPhone case, which is hooked to my belt and started clicking. The loud sharp clicks became hollow, soft clucks. After a few seconds the insect flew across the trail and started clicking from a branch. It then flew at me again and landed on the back of my leg, which offered even less resonance than the case. The cicada flew to another bush, clicked some more and then buzzed past my ear as it flew across the trail again. I left laughing. Interesting how important it's substrate is to the frequency of it's call.

Leaves and calyx ciliate, stems less than 1 cm, corolla tube glabrous outside; separates from similar, more regionally abundant M. tricolor/Diplacus tricolor.
